   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: `cJSON.c:798` dereferences `input_end` in `while
   (*input_end != '\"')` without first checking that `input_end` is still inside
   `input_buffer`. In the failing run, `input_buffer->content` points to the
   five-byte buffer `"abc\0`, `input_buffer->length` is `5`, and `input_end`
   starts at `content + 1`; because there is no closing quote, the loop advances
   over `a`, `b`, `c`, and the terminating NUL at index 4, then increments to
   `content + 5`. The next loop-condition evaluation reads `*input_end` at
   offset 5, which is one past the valid buffer range `[0, 4]`, so
   AddressSanitizer reports a heap-buffer-overflow and aborts before the later
   “string ended unexpectedly” check can run.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Restore a bounds check in the scan loop so the code never
   dereferences `input_end` after it reaches `input_buffer->length`; the
   existing post-loop check will then fail cleanly for unterminated strings.
